		<exercise>
			<title>Counting  functions</title>
			<idx><h>Counting  functions</h></idx>
			<statement>
				<p>
How many functions are there from <m>\{a,b,c,d \}</m> to <m>\{x,y,z \}</m>? This time, justify your answer with an argument rather than listing all possible functions.

<!--solution>
<p>
There are <m>3^4</m> functions. Each of the four elements in the domain can map to any of the three elements in the target. The result follows from the product principle.
</p>
</solution-->

