		<exercise>
			<title>Injective? Surjective?</title>
			<idx><h>Injective? Surjective?</h></idx>
			<statement>
				<p>
For each of the functions below, decide whether it is injective and/or surjective. If it does not satisfy the property, explain why by giving an example that violates the property. If it does satisfy the property, then provide a proof.



			<ol>

				<li>
					<p>
 <m>f: \Z \rightarrow \Z</m> given by <m>\displaystyle{f(n) = \left\lfloor \frac{n}{2} \right\rfloor}</m> where
<m>\left\lfloor x \right\rfloor</m> is the floor function, which "rounds down" to the nearest integer.

<!--solution>
<p>
		<ul>

			<li>
			<p>
 The function is not injective. For example, <m>f(0) = 0 = f(1)</m>

			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 The function is surjective. Given any <m>n \in Z</m>, we have <m>f(2n)=n</m>.

			</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
</p>
</solution-->

					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
 <m>g: \Z \rightarrow \Z</m> given by <m>g(n) = 4n -1</m>

<!--solution>
<p>
		<ul>

			<li>
			<p>
 The function is  injective. Suppose that <m>g(n) = g(m)</m>. This means that <m>4n-1=4m-1</m>, so <m>4n=4m</m> and finally <m>n=m</m>.

			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 The function is not surjective. It certainly misses all of the even numbers since the right hand side is odd. But we just need one counter example, so let's show that <m>g(n) \neq 0</m> for all <m>n \in \Z</m>. AFSOC (assume for the sake of contradiction) that <m>g(n) =0</m>. Then <m>0=4n-1</m> which means that <m>n=1/4</m>. But <m>1/4 \notin \Z</m>. Therefore, no element maps to <m>0</m>.

			</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
</p>
</solution-->

					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
 <m>h: \R \backslash \{ 0 \} \rightarrow \R</m> given by <m>\displaystyle{h(x) = \frac{x+1}{x}}</m>.

<!--solution>
<p>
		<ul>

			<li>
			<p>
 The function is  injective. This function is equivalent to <m>\displaystyle{h(x) = 1+\frac{1}{x}}</m>. Suppose that <m>f(a) = f(b)</m>. This means that
<me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
1+\frac{1}{a} &amp;=&amp; 1+\frac{1}{b} \\
\frac{1}{a} &amp;=&amp; \frac{1}{b} \\
a &amp;=&amp; b.
\end{array}
</me>

			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 The function is not surjective. It misses the point <m>y=1</m>. Indeed, if <m>h(x)=1</m> then
<me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
1 &amp;=&amp; 1+\frac{1}{x} \\
0 &amp;=&amp; \frac{1}{x}, \\
\end{array}
</me>
which is impossible.

			</p>
			</li>
		</ul>

</p>
</solution-->




